            "last_activity_date": 1409481829,
            "creation_date": 1409481829,
            "body": "<p>I found my problem, it was not a problem with the cache it was with the Persistence Manager.<\/p>\n\n<p>I was using 2 instances of the PM and this was the reason for the discrepancies.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25591186,
            "question_id": 25589524
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zCouy.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 1272202,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1228228,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1228228/alok-chaudhary",
                "reputation": 3511,
                "display_name": "Alok Chaudhary",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1409468642,
            "creation_date": 1409468642,
            "body": "<p>You can try configure your server.Assuming apache:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code># mod_expires directives: \n# enable expires/max-age headers and set default to 0 seconds from last access time\nExpiresActive On\nExpiresDefault A0\n# configure ExpiresByType on your specific types, eg ExpiresByType text/css A0\n\n# mod_headers directives:\n# send variety of no-cache directives, should cover any quirky clients and gateways\nHeader set Cache-Control \"max-age=0, private, no-cache, no-store, must-revalidate, proxy-revalidate, no-transform\"\nHeader set Pragma \"no-cache\"\n# enclose this in &lt;Files&gt; directive for specific file eg &lt;Files *.js&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>This is a good article on explaining caching for webpages: <a href=\"http://www.mnot.net/cache_docs/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.mnot.net/cache_docs/<\/a><\/p>\n",
